<br>
Right.  And Liability coverage would be the primary coverage her sister would be seeking compensation for.  IE:  Bodily injury coverage covers the injuries caused to Nandaries sister by the 20 year old. <br>
<br>
However, I would assume youre referring to my comment to Meann.  In this cas, Liability would also apply.  The term liability encompasses two coverages.  &quot;Bodiliy injury and property damage&quot;  All states except florida require bodily injury.  In Meann's case, the other party sped through the intersection, causing 'property damage&quot; to Meann's vehicle.  Seeing as though this is listed as &quot;liability&quot; it is wholly possible for the claim to be force paid under the statewide law that &quot;insurance follows the vehicle.&quot;  Any additional injuries or damages sustained by the claimant (in this case, Meann and her father) can be pursused against the driver.  If the driver had actually had insurance, his insurance would be considered secondary to the insurance of the registered owner of the car.<br>
<br>
The reason people become mis informed is because insurance companies will say we refuse to pay the claim for x, y, z.  Most people are too lazy to actually research who is primary, who is secondary and how it would be covered.  Most people just accept the insurance companys answer and dont pursue it because they think they cant win. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://ro0t.com/~hayley/HayleySig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
